      "id": "theory_bin_to_oct",
      "title": "Binary to Octal: The 3-Bit Grouping Method",
      "content": "Converting binary to octal is super easy! Each octal digit represents exactly 3 binary bits.\n\n**The 3-Bit Grouping Method:**\n\n1. Start from the RIGHT side of the binary number\n2. Group the bits into sets of 3\n3. If the leftmost group has fewer than 3 bits, add leading zeros\n4. Convert each 3-bit group to its octal digit (0-7)\n5. Combine the octal digits\n\n**Reference Table:**\n000 = 0    010 = 2    100 = 4    110 = 6\n001 = 1    011 = 3    101 = 5    111 = 7\n\n**Example 1: Convert 110101 to octal**\n\nStep 1: Group from right: 110 101\nStep 2: Convert each group:\n  \u2022 110 = 6\n  \u2022 101 = 5\nResult: 65\n\n**Example 2: Convert 11010110 to octal**\n\nStep 1: Group from right: 11 010 110\nStep 2: Pad left group: 011 010 110\nStep 3: Convert:\n  \u2022 011 = 3\n  \u2022 010 = 2\n  \u2022 110 = 6\nResult: 326\n\n**Example 3: Convert 1111111 to octal**\n\nStep 1: Group from right: 1 111 111\nStep 2: Pad left: 001 111 111\nStep 3: Convert:\n  \u2022 001 = 1\n  \u2022 111 = 7\n  \u2022 111 = 7\nResult: 177\n\n**Why This Works:**\nEach octal digit (0-7) represents values 0-7, which is exactly what 3 bits can represent (2\u00b3=8 values)!\n\n**Pro Tips:**\n\u2022 Always group from RIGHT to LEFT\n\u2022 Memorize the 8 conversions (000-111 to 0-7)\n\u2022 Compare to hex: hex uses 4-bit groups, octal uses 3-bit groups\n\u2022 This is MUCH faster than converting to decimal first!"
    },
